Given a BST and two nodes p and q, find their lowest common ancestor (LCA). The LCA is the lowest node in the tree that has both p and q as descendants (a node can be a descendant of itself).
        

Example:
                6
               / \
              2   8
             / \ / \
            0  4 7  9
              / \
             3   5
        
        p = 2, q = 8
        Output: 6
        
        p = 2, q = 4
        Output: 2


/*
 * Problem: Lowest Common Ancestor of BST
 * Pattern: Tree DFS + BST property
 * Time: O(h), Space: O(h) — O(log n) balanced, O(n) skewed
 * Key insight: BST property tells you exactly which direction to go
 * If both p,q < root → go left. Both > root → go right. Otherwise → root is LCA
 * Gotcha: root.val not root.value
 * Gotcha: always add null check even if problem guarantees valid input
 */



static TreeNode lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode root, TreeNode p, TreeNode q){
	
	if(root == null) return null;	

	if(root.value > val && root.value > val)	
		return lowestCommonAncestor(root.left, p,q);
	
	if(root.value < p.val && root.value < q.val)	
		return lowestCommonAncestor(root.right, p,q);
	
	else return root;
}
